Al-Shabaab fighters march with their weapons during military exercises in Somalia. (Mohamed Sheikh Nor, AP/File) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Nairobi - A Kenyan police official says two men arrested with a car bomb on Kenya's coast were in contact with the plotters of the September terrorist attack on an upmarket mall in Nairobi that killed at least 67 people.The official, who insisted on anonymity because he is not authorised to speak with the media, said on Monday that the vehicle was packed with 173kg of explosives and was meant to target a shopping mall in Mombasa. The official said the two arrested men spoke on the phone with militants in Somalia connected to the Westgate Mall attack.Kenya has experienced dozens of small bomb and gunfire attacks since al-Qaeda-linked Somali militants from al-Shabaab vowed to attack Kenya in retaliation for sending troops to Somalia in October 2011.24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.